reach to the very foundations of the modern human experience. As Engel shows, in his search for the truth of Jewish mysticism Scholem molded the vast literature of Jewish mystical lore into a rich assortment of stories that unveiled new truths about the modern condition. Positioning Scholem’s work and life within early twentieth-century Germany, Palestine, and later the state of Israel, Engel intertwines Scholem’s biography with his historiographical work, which stretches back to the Spanish expulsion of Jews in 1492, through the lives of Rabbi Isaac Luria and Sabbatai Zevi, and up to Hasidism and the dawn of the Zionist movement. Through parallel narratives, Engel touches on a wide array of important topics including immigration, exile, Zionism, World War One, and the creation of the state of Israel, ultimately telling the story of the realizations—and failures—of a dream for a modern Jewish existence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aJewish scholarszGermanyvBiography. 0aJewish scholarszIsraelvBiography. 0aMysticismxJudaism. 0aZionismxHistoryy20th century. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aExile.  aGerman Jewish culture.  aGershom Scholem.  aHistoriography.  aHomecoming.  aJewish mysticism.  aMyth.  aZionism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022642863540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226428772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226428772/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles